    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Maximizing interlacing points to limit void space is exactly the right way to look at it. If you increase the weft density significantly while holding the warp density steady, you are essentially packing more horizontal threads into the existing vertical structure. This creates a much thicker, more robust matrix in the weft direction.\n\nDimensional stability will improve because the increased density of the weft threads provides greater internal resistance to stretching or shrinking along that axis. The fabric becomes less prone to distortion when subjected to tension or changes in humidity.\n\nRegarding barrier properties against fine particulate matter—that's where you really push the limits. Increasing the weft density directly enhances the barrier effect. You are creating a denser physical barrier against those tiny particles. The smaller the void space between the weft threads, the less opportunity there is for fine dust or particulate matter to migrate through the fabric structure. You are essentially creating a finer sieve, though woven structures are inherently more complex than simple sieves.",
